WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-GB

00:00:09.174 --> 00:00:10.340
Well good evening, everyone.

00:00:10.340 --> 00:00:11.910
It's great to see you here.

00:00:11.910 --> 00:00:16.470
I am very, very excited
about tonight because I have,

00:00:16.470 --> 00:00:19.090
surrounding me here,
an illustrious panel

00:00:19.090 --> 00:00:23.190
of some of the world's best--
and some of the world's

00:00:23.190 --> 00:00:27.670
most important, I should say--
particle accelerator physicists

00:00:27.670 --> 00:00:30.240
who are working on
the next generation

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:32.450
after the Large Hadron Collider.

00:00:32.450 --> 00:00:36.900
So just to get a little bit
of a status of where we're at,

00:00:36.900 --> 00:00:39.140
can I see a show of
hands for how many of you

00:00:39.140 --> 00:00:41.453
have heard of the Large
Hadron Collider before?

00:00:41.453 --> 00:00:42.380
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:42.380 --> 00:00:44.460
Good, the media
has done its job.

00:00:44.460 --> 00:00:45.080
Excellent.

00:00:45.080 --> 00:00:46.930
OK, so my name is Susie Sheehy.

00:00:46.930 --> 00:00:48.620
Thank you, Martin,
for the introduction.

00:00:48.620 --> 00:00:51.530
I'm an accelerator physicist
at the University of Oxford.

00:00:51.530 --> 00:00:53.556
And I tend to design
smaller machines

00:00:53.556 --> 00:00:54.930
for different
applications, which

00:00:54.930 --> 00:00:57.300
is what a lot of our
project, called Accelerators

00:00:57.300 --> 00:00:59.470
for Humanity, has been about.

00:00:59.470 --> 00:01:02.010
But we couldn't be talking
about particle accelerators

00:01:02.010 --> 00:01:04.379
unless we really
brought out the big guns

00:01:04.379 --> 00:01:07.660
and talked about accelerators
for particle physics.

00:01:07.660 --> 00:01:10.300
So I think you're aware
already that the Large Hadron

00:01:10.300 --> 00:01:14.050
Collider is the highest
energy hadron-- that

00:01:14.050 --> 00:01:16.570
is, proton collider--
ever built--

00:01:16.570 --> 00:01:19.470
27 kilometers in circumference,
underneath the border

00:01:19.470 --> 00:01:22.970
between France and
Switzerland, near Geneva.

00:01:22.970 --> 00:01:27.340
And it is doing a fantastic
job at colliding protons

00:01:27.340 --> 00:01:30.870
together and uncovering the
secrets of the universe.

00:01:30.870 --> 00:01:34.540
But I'm often asked, when I talk
about particle accelerators,

00:01:34.540 --> 00:01:36.930
well, what's going to come next?

00:01:36.930 --> 00:01:39.750
What is the next big
thing after the LHC?

00:01:39.750 --> 00:01:42.310
And that is, effectively,
what we're here to talk about.

00:01:42.310 --> 00:01:44.130
So the four people I
have surrounding me,

00:01:44.130 --> 00:01:46.610
I'll just give you a quick
introduction to each of them.

00:01:46.610 --> 00:01:48.770
And then I'm going to
ask them to introduce

00:01:48.770 --> 00:01:53.510
their kind of pet project,
or their ideas on what

00:01:53.510 --> 00:01:55.950
might be coming after the
Large Hadron Collider.

00:01:55.950 --> 00:01:58.700
So first, on your
left, my right,

00:01:58.700 --> 00:02:00.360
is professor Phil Burrows.

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:04.290
Phil is a professor in physics
at the University of Oxford

00:02:04.290 --> 00:02:06.870
and he's also the associate
director of the John Adams

00:02:06.870 --> 00:02:09.020
Institute for accelerated
science, which

00:02:09.020 --> 00:02:11.300
is one of two accelerated
institutes in the UK.

00:02:11.300 --> 00:02:13.300
And it's also the
one that I work in.

00:02:13.300 --> 00:02:17.310
(LAUGHING) So Phils's
actually in my department.

00:02:17.310 --> 00:02:21.070
So Phil actually did his degree
and PhD in particle physics,

00:02:21.070 --> 00:02:23.050
first at Oxford Uni.

00:02:23.050 --> 00:02:26.470
And then he actually move to the
USA for about a decade working

00:02:26.470 --> 00:02:28.780
at MIT, and on SLAC,
the linear collider,

00:02:28.780 --> 00:02:31.270
which was the first
electron-positron collider

00:02:31.270 --> 00:02:32.900
in the world.

00:02:32.900 --> 00:02:36.550
He then returned to Oxford,
then became a Professor

00:02:36.550 --> 00:02:37.980
at Queen Mary
University, and then

00:02:37.980 --> 00:02:40.840
came back to Oxford again--
you've spent a lot of time

00:02:40.840 --> 00:02:44.190
at Oxford, Phil-- as a professor
and in his current position

00:02:44.190 --> 00:02:46.140
as director of the John Adams.

00:02:46.140 --> 00:02:50.440
So Phil has been PI-- that
is, Principal Investigator--

00:02:50.440 --> 00:02:53.920
of the UK'S team on linear
electron-positron collider

00:02:53.920 --> 00:02:57.580
development and working on the
international linear collider

00:02:57.580 --> 00:02:59.704
and the compact
linear collider, which

00:02:59.704 --> 00:03:01.870
he'll explain a little bit
more about what those two

00:03:01.870 --> 00:03:03.270
projects are.

00:03:03.270 --> 00:03:06.650
He's been Principal Investigator
of the CLIC UK collaboration

00:03:06.650 --> 00:03:11.110
since 2011, and since 2014
has been the spokesperson

00:03:11.110 --> 00:03:14.020
of the CLIC-- that is,
Compact Linear Accelerator

00:03:14.020 --> 00:03:16.420
Collaboration-- which
involves about 300 people,

00:03:16.420 --> 00:03:20.290
60 institutes, and 31
countries around the world.

00:03:20.290 --> 00:03:21.752
All right, so that's Phil.

00:03:21.752 --> 00:03:22.710
Could you welcome Phil?

00:03:22.710 --> 00:03:23.570
Give him a round of applause.

00:03:23.570 --> 00:03:24.321
Thank you.

00:03:24.321 --> 00:03:27.480
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:28.280 --> 00:03:29.250
OK.

00:03:29.250 --> 00:03:32.860
So the next person on the
line is Dr. Frank Zimmermann.

00:03:32.860 --> 00:03:34.640
Now I'm particularly
excited to have Frank

00:03:34.640 --> 00:03:36.765
here because Frank's actually
come all the way over

00:03:36.765 --> 00:03:37.280
from CERN.

00:03:37.280 --> 00:03:40.550
Frank is a senior scientist at
CERN in the Accelerator Beams

00:03:40.550 --> 00:03:43.390
department, which is obviously
the home of the Large Hadron

00:03:43.390 --> 00:03:44.680
Collider.

00:03:44.680 --> 00:03:47.800
Frank has worked, it seems,
on just about every project--

00:03:47.800 --> 00:03:51.520
major project
going, did his Ph.D

00:03:51.520 --> 00:03:54.330
at the University of Hamburg
on a machine called HERA, which

00:03:54.330 --> 00:03:57.460
is a proton ring, and has worked
at major labs around the world,

00:03:57.460 --> 00:04:00.150
including DESY in
Germany, SLAK in the US,

00:04:00.150 --> 00:04:03.980
and has worked at CERN
from 1999, I believe.

00:04:03.980 --> 00:04:06.800
So frank has published textbooks
in accelerated physics,

00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:09.610
wrote the handbook, he's the
editor of the main journal

00:04:09.610 --> 00:04:12.280
in the accelerated field-- The
Physical Review Accelerator,

00:04:12.280 --> 00:04:14.571
and Beams-- I know you're
going to rush out and read it

00:04:14.571 --> 00:04:15.910
right now.

00:04:15.910 --> 00:04:16.410
It's good.

00:04:16.410 --> 00:04:17.810
It's a good read, Frank.

00:04:17.810 --> 00:04:19.570
It's good.

00:04:19.570 --> 00:04:22.350
He's also a coordinator
of a work package of one

00:04:22.350 --> 00:04:24.110
of the major
European coordination

00:04:24.110 --> 00:04:28.020
in accelerator research and
development, called EuCARD.

00:04:28.020 --> 00:04:29.930
The work package is
called Extreme Beams,

00:04:29.930 --> 00:04:33.830
which is kind of cool-- I
like it-- and since 2014,

00:04:33.830 --> 00:04:36.910
has also been deputy coordinator
of the CERN-hosted Future

00:04:36.910 --> 00:04:39.900
Circular Collider Study,
which is mostly, I think,

00:04:39.900 --> 00:04:41.890
what you'll be addressing
tonight, hopefully.

00:04:41.890 --> 00:04:43.296
So please, welcome Frank.

00:04:43.296 --> 00:04:46.346
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:48.080 --> 00:04:50.530
OK, so first on my
left, you're right,

00:04:50.530 --> 00:04:52.570
this is Professor
Ken Long who is

00:04:52.570 --> 00:04:56.990
a professor of particle physics
at Imperial College in London.

00:04:56.990 --> 00:04:59.710
And he's done a
lot of work at CERN

00:04:59.710 --> 00:05:03.760
on muon-proton scattering as a
graduate student, apparently,

00:05:03.760 --> 00:05:09.560
and then returned to the
UK to join an experiment

00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:10.590
at DESY in Hamburg.

00:05:10.590 --> 00:05:13.230
In fact, these two discovered
they were almost colleagues

00:05:13.230 --> 00:05:17.064
at DESY by-- one year,
I think we discovered?--

00:05:17.064 --> 00:05:19.480
and has contributed to the
design and construction of that

00:05:19.480 --> 00:05:23.170
experiment-- so that's
particle physics experiment.

00:05:23.170 --> 00:05:25.420
Now Ken got fascinated
by the discovery

00:05:25.420 --> 00:05:27.580
of neutrino oscillations
at one point in career.

00:05:27.580 --> 00:05:30.600
And your career seems
to have turned direction

00:05:30.600 --> 00:05:34.020
and really focus on neutrinos
and muons since that time.

00:05:34.020 --> 00:05:36.610
So Ken chairs the
international design study

00:05:36.610 --> 00:05:39.190
for a machine called the
Neutrino Factory, which

00:05:39.190 --> 00:05:41.920
hopefully we'll hear more
about, and is spokesman

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:44.760
for an experiment called
the Muon Ionization Cooling

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:47.400
Experiment, which is being
carried out at the Rutherford

00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:51.150
Appleton lab in
Oxfordshire-- and is also

00:05:51.150 --> 00:05:53.300
chair of the International
Committee for Future

00:05:53.300 --> 00:05:55.010
Accelerators, Neutrino Panel.

00:05:55.010 --> 00:05:59.467
So Ken focuses mostly on
neutrino and muon accelerators

00:05:59.467 --> 00:06:00.050
at the moment.

00:06:00.050 --> 00:06:01.720
So please, welcome Ken.

00:06:06.610 --> 00:06:10.310
And finally, but by no means
least, Stuart Mangles-- Dr.

00:06:10.310 --> 00:06:12.240
Stuart Mangles, on
my far left here,

00:06:12.240 --> 00:06:15.270
is a senior lecturer in physics
at Imperial College London

00:06:15.270 --> 00:06:17.401
where he also did his PhD.

00:06:17.401 --> 00:06:19.650
And he is a faculty member
of the John Adams Institute

00:06:19.650 --> 00:06:21.190
as well, I should say.

00:06:21.190 --> 00:06:25.440
Now Stuart's focus is a little
different from the other four

00:06:25.440 --> 00:06:26.610
of us here, in fact.

00:06:26.610 --> 00:06:29.860
In that, he's actually, by
definition, a plasma physicist,

00:06:29.860 --> 00:06:30.360
I suppose.

00:06:30.360 --> 00:06:33.330
So he researches
plasma-based accelerators.

00:06:33.330 --> 00:06:35.960
And he's been doing that
for the past 15 years

00:06:35.960 --> 00:06:39.710
using a technique called
Laser Wakefield Acceleration.

00:06:39.710 --> 00:06:42.480
So Stuart has a growing
interest in that field,

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:45.640
in both developing laser
Wakefield accelerators--

00:06:45.640 --> 00:06:48.260
both for particle physics
and for other applications--

00:06:48.260 --> 00:06:50.920
and improving the quality
of the beams from them.

00:06:50.920 --> 00:06:53.400
He's also involved in
a project at DESY lab--

00:06:53.400 --> 00:06:55.940
DESY keeps cropping up, doesn't
it?-- called Flash Forward,

00:06:55.940 --> 00:06:58.940
which will use intense beams
of electrons to drive a plasma

00:06:58.940 --> 00:06:59.680
wave.

00:06:59.680 --> 00:07:02.221
So that's not going to make a
huge amount of sense right now,

00:07:02.221 --> 00:07:05.150
but it will when Stuart gives us
a bit of an introduction later.

00:07:05.150 --> 00:07:06.670
So please, welcome Stuart.

00:07:06.670 --> 00:07:10.116
