kind of introduction-pitch

00:07:24.910 --> 00:07:27.360
to the types of projects
that they work on

00:07:27.360 --> 00:07:30.050
that they think might
happen in the future.

00:07:30.050 --> 00:07:33.760
So the first contribution
to that is Phil Burrows.

00:07:33.760 --> 00:07:37.591
So hopefully we have
some slides to go along.

00:07:37.591 --> 00:07:38.340
Over to you, Phil.

00:07:38.340 --> 00:07:38.840
OK.

00:07:38.840 --> 00:07:40.130
Thank you very much, Susie.

00:07:40.130 --> 00:07:41.310
Is the microphone working?

00:07:41.310 --> 00:07:42.300
Can everybody hear me?

00:07:42.300 --> 00:07:43.231
OK, super.

00:07:43.231 --> 00:07:45.730
Well, ladies and gentlemen thank
you very much for giving up

00:07:45.730 --> 00:07:49.620
a rather lovely Friday evening
in September to come and join

00:07:49.620 --> 00:07:52.850
is in this conversation
about possible future large

00:07:52.850 --> 00:07:54.350
accelerator projects.

00:07:54.350 --> 00:07:56.270
Now you've already
identified yourselves

00:07:56.270 --> 00:07:59.190
as a very erudite audience
because everybody's heard

00:07:59.190 --> 00:08:01.280
of the Large Hadron Collider.

00:08:01.280 --> 00:08:05.430
And everybody knows that large
modern, high-energy particle

00:08:05.430 --> 00:08:08.560
accelerators are
circular, such as the LHC

00:08:08.560 --> 00:08:10.290
that you see on the
photograph here.

00:08:10.290 --> 00:08:13.700
Well they're circular, that
is, except when they're not.

00:08:13.700 --> 00:08:17.990
And so this is a photograph
of the two-mile long linear

00:08:17.990 --> 00:08:20.140
collider at Stanford
in California.

00:08:20.140 --> 00:08:22.400
And in fact, frank and
I had the privilege

00:08:22.400 --> 00:08:25.460
to work together on this
project in the 1990s.

00:08:25.460 --> 00:08:27.630
And you can see,
manifestly, that it is

00:08:27.630 --> 00:08:30.040
linear-- it is two miles long.

00:08:30.040 --> 00:08:32.610
So what do we do?

00:08:32.610 --> 00:08:35.200
What do we want to do with
linear electron-positron

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:35.700
colliders?

00:08:35.700 --> 00:08:38.220
Well we want to take
subatomic particles--

00:08:38.220 --> 00:08:40.830
electrons-- we want
to collide them

00:08:40.830 --> 00:08:43.010
with their
anti-matter partners--

00:08:43.010 --> 00:08:46.090
positrons, which have the
opposite electric charge.

00:08:46.090 --> 00:08:49.080
When electrons meet positrons,
matter and anti-matter

00:08:49.080 --> 00:08:52.840
annihilate, energy is
released, and condenses

00:08:52.840 --> 00:08:55.470
out of that energy
are exciting types

00:08:55.470 --> 00:08:58.209
of new elementary particles,
for example, the Higgs bosons,

00:08:58.209 --> 00:09:00.000
which I'm sure most of
you will have heard.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.940
It was discovered only a
couple of years ago at CERN.

00:09:02.940 --> 00:09:06.740
For example, top quarks,
which are very heavy types

00:09:06.740 --> 00:09:09.030
of subatomic building
blocks of matter.

00:09:09.030 --> 00:09:11.730
And of course, who knows,
maybe dark matter particle,

00:09:11.730 --> 00:09:13.970
supersymmetric
particles, something

00:09:13.970 --> 00:09:17.620
that has yet to be discovered
about which we would be very

00:09:17.620 --> 00:09:19.960
excited and very keen to know.

00:09:19.960 --> 00:09:21.970
So linear
electron-positron colliders

00:09:21.970 --> 00:09:26.530
are the way forward to serve
as factories for mass-producing

00:09:26.530 --> 00:09:29.080
Higgs bosons, top
quarks, and hopefully,

00:09:29.080 --> 00:09:31.260
dark matter and other
types of new particles.

00:09:31.260 --> 00:09:33.850
We're talking about hundreds
of thousands of Higgs bosons,

00:09:33.850 --> 00:09:36.244
hundreds of thousands of
top corks-- samples that

00:09:36.244 --> 00:09:38.160
will allow us to really
measure the properties

00:09:38.160 --> 00:09:40.940
of these particles with
exquisite precision

00:09:40.940 --> 00:09:43.260
and understand what they are.

00:09:43.260 --> 00:09:46.790
Now there are two major projects
which are being proposed

00:09:46.790 --> 00:09:51.235
for implementation for
high-energy future E+, E-

00:09:51.235 --> 00:09:52.970
electron-positron
linear colliders.

00:09:52.970 --> 00:09:55.640
This one is the international
linear collider.

00:09:55.640 --> 00:09:58.450
To cut a long story short,
you stick electrons in at one

00:09:58.450 --> 00:10:00.800
end you, stick positrons
in at the other end,

00:10:00.800 --> 00:10:02.640
you accelerate them
together, and you

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:05.090
do matter-anti-matter
annihilations in the middle.

00:10:05.090 --> 00:10:07.490
The rest of the detail, you
don't need to worry about.

00:10:07.490 --> 00:10:10.350
The footprint of this machine
is about 30 kilometers.

00:10:10.350 --> 00:10:13.610
Our friends in Japan
have-- the particle

00:10:13.610 --> 00:10:15.950
physics community
in Japan very much

00:10:15.950 --> 00:10:19.230
wants to host this machine in
the northern part of Japan just

00:10:19.230 --> 00:10:20.692
north of the city of Sendai.

00:10:20.692 --> 00:10:23.150
You can see on the map there,
the footprint of the machine.

00:10:23.150 --> 00:10:25.460
If you look closely, you
can see a cross-section

00:10:25.460 --> 00:10:28.500
through the geology of the
mountains in the Kitakami

00:10:28.500 --> 00:10:29.000
region.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:31.390
So this project,
we hope very much,

00:10:31.390 --> 00:10:34.790
will be realized in Japan.

00:10:34.790 --> 00:10:37.380
Now another project, which
is perhaps a little bit

00:10:37.380 --> 00:10:41.830
further away, is the
compact linear collider.

00:10:41.830 --> 00:10:44.510
And I, as Susie said,
I'm privileged to be

00:10:44.510 --> 00:10:46.880
the spokesman-- or if
you like, Principal

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:49.570
Investigator-- of this project.

00:10:49.570 --> 00:10:51.444
Again, don't worry
about the details.

00:10:51.444 --> 00:10:53.860
It's a slightly bigger version
of the international linear

00:10:53.860 --> 00:10:54.359
collider.

00:10:54.359 --> 00:10:56.980
It's designed to get to
somewhat higher energies

00:10:56.980 --> 00:10:58.320
of these collisions.

00:10:58.320 --> 00:11:01.050
And never let it be said that
accelerator physicists don't

00:11:01.050 --> 00:11:03.620
have a sense of humor
because compact means

00:11:03.620 --> 00:11:05.630
50 kilometers long.

00:11:05.630 --> 00:11:07.290
But that's a jolly
sight more compact

00:11:07.290 --> 00:11:08.940
than it would be
if it weren't made

00:11:08.940 --> 00:11:11.020
with this wonderful technology.

00:11:11.020 --> 00:11:13.690
As Susie mentioned, I think it's
important to note that these

00:11:13.690 --> 00:11:15.010
are global scale projects.

00:11:15.010 --> 00:11:17.770
So in the case of the
Compact Linear Collider,

00:11:17.770 --> 00:11:20.260
300 people, 50
institutes, 31 countries.

00:11:20.260 --> 00:11:22.690
So my joke, at this
point, is the sun never

00:11:22.690 --> 00:11:24.960
sets on my empire.

00:11:24.960 --> 00:11:27.210
Now if that project
were realized,

00:11:27.210 --> 00:11:29.530
it would be realized in
the Geneva region at CERN.

00:11:29.530 --> 00:11:30.750
So here you see a little map.

00:11:30.750 --> 00:11:32.291
The little white
circle in the middle

00:11:32.291 --> 00:11:33.990
is the Large Hadron Collider.

00:11:33.990 --> 00:11:35.820
And then you can
see magenta, green,

00:11:35.820 --> 00:11:38.690
and blue linear arrays of dots.

00:11:38.690 --> 00:11:40.610
And those represent
the different stages

00:11:40.610 --> 00:11:42.780
of this project,
leading eventually

00:11:42.780 --> 00:11:46.490
to an energy of 3,000
giga-electron volts--

00:11:46.490 --> 00:11:49.890
or accelerating
particles-- to energies

00:11:49.890 --> 00:11:54.500
of 1.5 trillion volts
for the electrons,

00:11:54.500 --> 00:11:56.530
and 1.5 trillion volts
for the positrons.

00:11:56.530 --> 00:11:59.350
So these are very
high energy machines.

00:11:59.350 --> 00:12:02.380
So what I would hope
to argue this evening

00:12:02.380 --> 00:12:04.200
is that the way ahead is linear.

00:12:04.200 --> 00:12:05.800
Linear colliders
allow collisions

00:12:05.800 --> 00:12:08.570
of point-like particles
under controlled conditions.

00:12:08.570 --> 00:12:10.300
They allow
factory-level production

00:12:10.300 --> 00:12:12.940
of things such as Higgs
bosons, which we really

00:12:12.940 --> 00:12:14.690
need to understand
having just discovered

00:12:14.690 --> 00:12:16.710
them a few years ago.

00:12:16.710 --> 00:12:18.050
Why linear?

00:12:18.050 --> 00:12:20.360
Well, the problem--
and Frank, of course,

00:12:20.360 --> 00:12:23.110
will talk about this
in his presentation--

00:12:23.110 --> 00:12:26.160
when you try to accelerate
electrons or positrons

00:12:26.160 --> 00:12:28.680
in a circle, they emit x-rays.

00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:30.150
This is call
synchrotron radiation.

00:12:30.150 --> 00:12:31.760
And at some point,
as fast as you

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:35.210
are trying to accelerate them,
they're radiating energy away.

00:12:35.210 --> 00:12:36.650
And so it's generally
agreed that,

00:12:36.650 --> 00:12:38.540
to get to the very
highest energies,

00:12:38.540 --> 00:12:41.100
one should avoid this
synchrotron radiation.

00:12:41.100 --> 00:12:44.630
And therefore, the
future is linear machines

00:12:44.630 --> 00:12:46.290
with no synchrotron radiation.

00:12:46.290 --> 00:12:48.920
They're elegantly expandable
because you can always

00:12:48.920 --> 00:12:50.520
make them that bit longer.

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:52.700
and therefore get
to higher energies.

00:12:52.700 --> 00:12:54.920
And they are
intrinsically upgradable

00:12:54.920 --> 00:12:58.640
because, once you have your
nice 30-kilometer-long tunnel,

00:12:58.640 --> 00:13:02.250
when Stuart comes along in 50
years when his technology is

00:13:02.250 --> 00:13:06.900
working, you can always stick
it into this beautiful tunnel

00:13:06.900 --> 00:13:08.370
and you can get
to higher energies

00:13:08.370 --> 00:13:12.300
by upgrading the facility that
you have as technology comes

00:13:12.300 --> 00:13:15.050
along and as you're able to get
to higher and higher energies--

00:13:15.050 --> 00:13:18.380
so elegantly expandable and
intrinsically upgradable.

00:13:18.380 --> 00:13:20.130
And the technologies
that we're developing

00:13:20.130 --> 00:13:22.360
with many applications--
this is my last couple

00:13:22.360 --> 00:13:24.440
of slides, Susie,
as you know-- this

00:13:24.440 --> 00:13:27.110
is the European x-ray-free
electron laser at the DESY

00:13:27.110 --> 00:13:29.206
laboratorY-- again, in Hamburg.

00:13:29.206 --> 00:13:31.580
And the technology that we've
developed-- superconducting

00:13:31.580 --> 00:13:33.875
niobium radio-frequency
accelerating cavity

00:13:33.875 --> 00:13:37.230
is the shiny thing,
bottom left, there.

00:13:37.230 --> 00:13:40.590
This technology developed for
these big high-energy machines,

00:13:40.590 --> 00:13:42.520
such as the International
linear collider,

00:13:42.520 --> 00:13:44.650
has now been deployed in
the two-kilometer machine

00:13:44.650 --> 00:13:45.160
in Hamburg.

00:13:45.160 --> 00:13:49.970
It's a 10% scale model
of the real machine.

00:13:49.970 --> 00:13:52.230
And this will serve tens
of thousands of scientists

00:13:52.230 --> 00:13:55.080
by producing x-rays to look
at the structure of matter,

00:13:55.080 --> 00:13:57.210
materials through
structural biology,

00:13:57.210 --> 00:13:59.370
do biomedicine,
chemistry, and so on.

00:13:59.370 --> 00:14:00.870
So this is an example
of the spinoff

00:14:00.870 --> 00:14:03.870
of the technology for the
great benefit of wider science.

00:14:03.870 --> 00:14:05.990
And I love this slide.

00:14:05.990 --> 00:14:07.820
This is another example
of the application

00:14:07.820 --> 00:14:09.990
of linear accelerating
technology.

00:14:09.990 --> 00:14:11.420
The gentlemen, in
the bottom left,

00:14:11.420 --> 00:14:14.220
are carrying a
roughly 1-meter-long

00:14:14.220 --> 00:14:16.860
accelerating structure
made of copper.

00:14:16.860 --> 00:14:18.729
They've developed
structures like that

00:14:18.729 --> 00:14:20.770
for the purpose of getting
to the high energies--

00:14:20.770 --> 00:14:23.170
the big, two-mile long machine
at Stanford that you see

00:14:23.170 --> 00:14:25.790
upstairs-- and
today, there is one

00:14:25.790 --> 00:14:30.820
of those structures in more
than 10,000 x-ray therapy

00:14:30.820 --> 00:14:32.950
machines that have been
deployed in hospitals

00:14:32.950 --> 00:14:33.810
all over the world.

00:14:33.810 --> 00:14:36.480
There are more than 10,000
of these machines worldwide.

00:14:36.480 --> 00:14:39.970
And in the UK alone,
10,000 people, per day,

00:14:39.970 --> 00:14:42.760
are treated with cancer
therapy from machines

00:14:42.760 --> 00:14:45.020
like this which are
employing technology

00:14:45.020 --> 00:14:48.840
developed with a view to very
high-energy linear colliders.

00:14:48.840 --> 00:14:50.950
So I think at that
point, I'd better stop.

00:14:50.950 --> 00:14:52.450
And I'll give my
colleagues a chance

00:14:52.450 --> 00:14:54.815
