00:34:56.060 --> 00:34:58.700
So one of the key things I
should point out at this stage

00:34:58.700 --> 00:35:00.910
is that one of the
useful things about muons

00:35:00.910 --> 00:35:02.710
is, because they're
slightly heavier,

00:35:02.710 --> 00:35:04.800
they emit less
synchrotron radiation.

00:35:04.800 --> 00:35:07.662
So this issue of the
being losing energy

00:35:07.662 --> 00:35:09.620
as it goes around the
ring is not such an issue

00:35:09.620 --> 00:35:11.450
in the muon collider, right?

00:35:11.450 --> 00:35:12.120
Could I--

00:35:12.120 --> 00:35:12.620
Yeah.

00:35:12.620 --> 00:35:14.060
So I think that
the point to make

00:35:14.060 --> 00:35:15.660
is that, if you're
radiating energy,

00:35:15.660 --> 00:35:17.430
but you want to keep
colliding at the same energy,

00:35:17.430 --> 00:35:18.730
you got to put the energy back.

00:35:18.730 --> 00:35:21.260
And that has to come out
of the power station.

00:35:21.260 --> 00:35:25.020
So if you radiate less energy,
you have to put less power in.

00:35:25.020 --> 00:35:26.915
And that's why there
is an energy, about one

00:35:26.915 --> 00:35:29.080
and a half TeV, where
the muon colliders are

00:35:29.080 --> 00:35:33.660
more cost effective to
operate, maybe not to build.

00:35:33.660 --> 00:35:34.830
OK.

00:35:34.830 --> 00:35:38.736
Right, so now onto something
completely different.

00:35:38.736 --> 00:35:40.360
Yeah, I don't think
I need to introduce

00:35:40.360 --> 00:35:42.401
any further than that,
just completely different.

00:35:42.401 --> 00:35:43.698
Go ahead, Stuart.

00:35:43.698 --> 00:35:45.960
Hang on-- oh.

00:35:45.960 --> 00:35:47.990
Starting on the wrong one.

00:35:47.990 --> 00:35:51.640
So, so far, you've heard about
all these different particle

00:35:51.640 --> 00:35:53.740
accelerators and
future projects.

00:35:53.740 --> 00:35:55.710
And I think they have
one thing in common--

00:35:55.710 --> 00:35:57.800
they're all massive machines.

00:35:57.800 --> 00:36:01.010
And so the question
I'm looking at

00:36:01.010 --> 00:36:03.340
is, why are they so big,
and more importantly,

00:36:03.340 --> 00:36:05.520
can we make them a lot smaller?

00:36:05.520 --> 00:36:08.800
So Phil was right, I'm not sure
if I agree about the 50 years.

00:36:08.800 --> 00:36:12.047
But what we are talking
about a technology

00:36:12.047 --> 00:36:14.005
that could be used a bit
further in the future.

00:36:14.005 --> 00:36:15.530
I'm very happy with that.

00:36:15.530 --> 00:36:17.440
Yeah

00:36:17.440 --> 00:36:21.480
And so, again, compulsory
picture-- overhead picture

00:36:21.480 --> 00:36:23.430
of a big accelerator.

00:36:23.430 --> 00:36:25.630
I went for SI units
rather than miles.

00:36:25.630 --> 00:36:28.220
It's about three
kilometers long.

00:36:28.220 --> 00:36:30.605
This is slack in America.

00:36:30.605 --> 00:36:32.980
And the thing is, that all of
these particle accelerators

00:36:32.980 --> 00:36:35.600
are basically using
the same technology

00:36:35.600 --> 00:36:37.490
to accelerate particles.

00:36:37.490 --> 00:36:40.480
Whether or not they're
accelerating electrons,

00:36:40.480 --> 00:36:43.740
protons, or muons they're
using an electric field

00:36:43.740 --> 00:36:46.970
to accelerate a particle
inside a vacuum tube.

00:36:46.970 --> 00:36:50.330
So it's a low-pressure vessel
with nothing inside it.

00:36:50.330 --> 00:36:52.480
And then you put a
radio frequency wave

00:36:52.480 --> 00:36:55.690
traveling through it, which
accelerates the particles up

00:36:55.690 --> 00:36:57.150
as it goes along.

00:36:57.150 --> 00:37:01.990
You can work out the energy
that your charged particle can

00:37:01.990 --> 00:37:05.147
get up to by just taking the
strength of the electric field,

00:37:05.147 --> 00:37:07.730
which is measured in volts per
meter-- or megavolts per meter,

00:37:07.730 --> 00:37:11.650
if you like-- million volts
per meter-- by the distance.

00:37:11.650 --> 00:37:14.350
Because they're all using
basically the same technology,

00:37:14.350 --> 00:37:18.860
they're all working at
around about 10 to 10--

00:37:18.860 --> 00:37:21.260
right at the top end--
100 megavolts per meter.

00:37:21.260 --> 00:37:23.180
So just some very simple
math, that tells you,

00:37:23.180 --> 00:37:25.240
if you want to get a
particle to just 1 GeV,

00:37:25.240 --> 00:37:30.120
you still need 10 to 100
meters of accelerator.

00:37:30.120 --> 00:37:32.024
If you want to get
to 100 GeV, you

00:37:32.024 --> 00:37:33.440
need, depending
on the technology,

00:37:33.440 --> 00:37:35.110
between 10 and 100 kilometers.

00:37:35.110 --> 00:37:38.340
I didn't put 100 TeV on there.

00:37:38.340 --> 00:37:39.930
But that was with those numbers.

00:37:39.930 --> 00:37:43.781
And so effectively, the only
way we can make things shorter

00:37:43.781 --> 00:37:45.030
is-- well, there are two ways.

00:37:45.030 --> 00:37:47.510
One is we can use the same
accelerating structure over

00:37:47.510 --> 00:37:49.510
and over again, which is
a circular accelerator.

00:37:49.510 --> 00:37:53.740
But then we hit the problem of
magnet strength and synchotron

00:37:53.740 --> 00:37:54.694
radiation.

00:37:54.694 --> 00:37:56.610
Or we can turn up the
electric field strength.

00:37:56.610 --> 00:37:59.200
They're basically the
only two things we can do.

00:37:59.200 --> 00:38:03.190
In fact, the technology to get
up to 100 megavolts per meter,

00:38:03.190 --> 00:38:04.850
that's already really hard.

00:38:04.850 --> 00:38:07.130
That's a really
cutting edge technology

00:38:07.130 --> 00:38:09.525
in vacuum accelerators.

00:38:12.007 --> 00:38:13.340
So why can't they go any higher?

00:38:13.340 --> 00:38:15.381
Well the problem is-- I
don't know if you've ever

00:38:15.381 --> 00:38:17.400
tried this-- but if
you have two electrodes

00:38:17.400 --> 00:38:19.460
and you put a lot of
voltage between them in air,

00:38:19.460 --> 00:38:21.650
you get a spark
forming between them.

00:38:21.650 --> 00:38:27.830
If you turn down the pressure--
so if you put that capacitor

00:38:27.830 --> 00:38:31.390
in vacuum-- you can put a
larger voltage before the vacuum

00:38:31.390 --> 00:38:33.000
before you get breakdown.

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:35.730
But it doesn't matter how
low in pressure you go,

00:38:35.730 --> 00:38:37.880
you will always get to the
point where there's just

00:38:37.880 --> 00:38:40.160
one electron-- one or two
electrons between those two

00:38:40.160 --> 00:38:42.020
plates and that will
cause an avalanche that

00:38:42.020 --> 00:38:44.050
will mean that you
get sparks forming

00:38:44.050 --> 00:38:45.390
inside your accelerator.

00:38:45.390 --> 00:38:47.640
And that's the sort of
fundamental limit of why,

00:38:47.640 --> 00:38:51.080
if you're using this
conventional technology

00:38:51.080 --> 00:38:53.280
to accelerate things,
you can't go any higher

00:38:53.280 --> 00:38:55.620
than about 100
megavolts per meter.

00:38:55.620 --> 00:38:57.580
And that's because
you turn up the field,

00:38:57.580 --> 00:38:59.634
and it's just going to
start forming sparks,

00:38:59.634 --> 00:39:01.050
which degrade the
whole structure,

00:39:01.050 --> 00:39:02.950
they may even destroy it.

00:39:02.950 --> 00:39:07.260
And so if you like, what
I'm trying to look at--

00:39:07.260 --> 00:39:10.600
and I have been over the
last decade or so-- is,

00:39:10.600 --> 00:39:12.690
could we do something else?

00:39:12.690 --> 00:39:16.160
Could we actually solve
this breakdown problem

00:39:16.160 --> 00:39:18.945
and start with something that
either-- well, one thing,

00:39:18.945 --> 00:39:19.980
it would be nice if you
could find something

00:39:19.980 --> 00:39:21.146
that just didn't break down.

00:39:21.146 --> 00:39:22.500
Not sure that exists.

00:39:22.500 --> 00:39:24.460
But instead, actually
do the exhilaration

00:39:24.460 --> 00:39:26.260
in something that's
already broken down.

00:39:26.260 --> 00:39:30.010
So if you take a volume of
gas, and you fully ionize it,

00:39:30.010 --> 00:39:31.290
it can't ionize anymore.

00:39:31.290 --> 00:39:32.920
And actually, that's
called a plasma.

00:39:32.920 --> 00:39:35.310
And plasmas can support
huge electric fields.

00:39:38.980 --> 00:39:42.350
I think we have already
demonstrated, sort of,

00:39:42.350 --> 00:39:45.266
fairly useful fields,
depending on your definition,

00:39:45.266 --> 00:39:48.650
at 10,000 megavolts per meter.

00:39:48.650 --> 00:39:52.410
So just to give you
an idea, I would

00:39:52.410 --> 00:39:54.660
say, compared to conventional
accelerators in its very

00:39:54.660 --> 00:39:57.540
early days-- we've been
doing things for a while,

00:39:57.540 --> 00:39:59.784
in my lifetime, and
in terms of how long

00:39:59.784 --> 00:40:01.825
I've been doing it and
significantly before me as

00:40:01.825 --> 00:40:07.910
well-- but there are-- did
my microphone just go off?

00:40:07.910 --> 00:40:09.910
Yeah, it's come back on.

00:40:09.910 --> 00:40:12.770
But there are definitely
things going on.

00:40:12.770 --> 00:40:15.850
So this picture
here is an overview

00:40:15.850 --> 00:40:18.890
of the Rutherford Appleton
Lab, one of the national labs

00:40:18.890 --> 00:40:19.770
in the UK here.

00:40:19.770 --> 00:40:23.640
And there are three GeV-- so
small-- particle accelerators

00:40:23.640 --> 00:40:24.900
in this picture.

00:40:24.900 --> 00:40:27.620
The first one is
at the top here.

00:40:27.620 --> 00:40:29.060
That's the diamond light source.

00:40:29.060 --> 00:40:31.100
It's a machine not for
doing particle physics

00:40:31.100 --> 00:40:33.200
but for making x-rays for
all sorts of scientists.

00:40:33.200 --> 00:40:37.690
And at the heart of it
is a 3 GeV electron beam.

00:40:37.690 --> 00:40:41.800
In the bottom here is ISIS,
which is a neutron source.

00:40:41.800 --> 00:40:44.380
And those neutrons are made by
accelerating protons and using

00:40:44.380 --> 00:40:47.930
a process called spallation
to make neutrons.

00:40:47.930 --> 00:40:50.720
And at the heart of that is 1
GeV proton accelerator-- .8,

00:40:50.720 --> 00:40:52.350
I think.

00:40:52.350 --> 00:40:54.700
So they're all
pretty big machines.

00:40:54.700 --> 00:40:57.360
Somewhere in that
building, in there, there

00:40:57.360 --> 00:41:01.940
is a pretty big laser called
Astro Gemini, which we're

00:41:01.940 --> 00:41:04.824
now fairly routinely
producing-- very messy compared

00:41:04.824 --> 00:41:06.740
to the beams that come
out of these machines--

00:41:06.740 --> 00:41:09.740
but 2 GeV beams
inside that lab there.

00:41:09.740 --> 00:41:13.200
The actual accelerator
is this long.

00:41:13.200 --> 00:41:15.890
So the actual plasmal
part is that long.

00:41:15.890 --> 00:41:19.230
And so the technology
we're working on

00:41:19.230 --> 00:41:21.170
is-- I really liked what
Phil said, which was,

00:41:21.170 --> 00:41:23.880
if you could imagine replacing
conventional accelerators

00:41:23.880 --> 00:41:25.900
with a plasma system,
you could suddenly

00:41:25.900 --> 00:41:27.259
make a massive upgrade.

00:41:27.259 --> 00:41:29.550
So that's the sort of thing--
the time scale we think--

00:41:29.550 --> 00:41:31.576
I think seems realistic.

00:41:31.576 --> 00:41:34.200
But just to give you an idea of
how much progress we're making,

00:41:34.200 --> 00:41:37.940
here, I've got a plot from
one of my PhD student's

00:41:37.940 --> 00:41:40.230
thesis, Jason Cole.

00:41:40.230 --> 00:41:45.050
So he took conventional electron
accelerators and there, energy

00:41:45.050 --> 00:41:47.120
as a function of
time-- so you can see

00:41:47.120 --> 00:41:49.270
they started back in the 1940s.

00:41:49.270 --> 00:41:52.230
And they made rapid progress
for the first 30 years,

00:41:52.230 --> 00:41:54.790
doubling energy about every
two years, I think it was.

00:41:54.790 --> 00:41:56.500
And then it kind of tailed off.

00:41:56.500 --> 00:41:59.000
And then you get plasma
accelerators which basically

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:00.710
started in the mid 90s.

00:42:00.710 --> 00:42:05.580
And we've been making similar
progress over the last 10

00:42:05.580 --> 00:42:07.330
years-- 10, 20 years as well.

00:42:07.330 --> 00:42:11.720
So our record is now,
the group at Berkeley

00:42:11.720 --> 00:42:13.490
have now produced 4
GeV electron beams

00:42:13.490 --> 00:42:17.700
in a plasma that's 9
centimeters long, so that big.

00:42:17.700 --> 00:42:20.310
And that corresponds to
an accelerating field that

00:42:20.310 --> 00:42:22.752
is 10,000 megavolts per meter.

00:42:22.752 --> 00:42:24.460
So I haven't done the
numbers, but if you

00:42:24.460 --> 00:42:26.520
wanted to do this
100 TeV machine,

00:42:26.520 --> 00:42:29.240
if you could use that it
would get a lot shorter.

00:42:29.240 --> 00:42:30.490
So that's what I'm working on.

00:42:30.490 --> 00:42:31.760
Thank you very much

00:42:31.760 --> 00:42:32.260
OK.

00:42:32.260 --> 00:42:33.900
Thanks.

